Tuesday September 17th 2013 8:23 am -04:00,objects are a special datatype which contain attributes and methods:1. object.attribute- retrieve attribute of object- i think the course did not cover the topic of attributes yet so i wont either.- object.method without the brackets does not exist2. object.method()- dot notation- call method on object- e.g. abc.find(a) returns 0 (because first occurence of a is at index 0)3. method(object)- some common methods have a different/shorter syntax - e.g. len(abc) returns 3- you maybe would expect abc.len(). this is wrong. - abc.__len__() does exist and also returns 3reference: type help(str) in IDLE , Unresolved,3
Wednesday September 18th 2013 4:19 am -04:00,i am a beginner and no authority on this matter but this is how i see it:theoryfunctional programming and object-oriented programming are two different perspectives to solve problems using code. The world of functional programming uses functions to construct programs and does not use classes objects or methods. The world of object-oriented programming uses classes objects and methods to construct programs and does not use functions. practiceIn Python we can use both perspectives and mix them up. method(object) is syntax from the object-oriented world which produces the same outcome as function(x) from the functional programming world. , Unresolved,0
